annotations: With that ‘you’re on camera’ smile
This lyric refers to a sign used to deter shoplifters that says “Smile! You’re on camera.”
[Verse 2: Phoebe Bridgers]

Katie wrote my verse, she wrote my verse as Phoebe Bridgers cosplay basically. She knew I would talk about being stoned in CVS, which I love. I’m gonna have her write all my songs now.

– Phoebe Bridgers, Reverse The Verse, March 2022
Downtown, cherry lipstick
Cherry lipstick and chapstick are often used as a queer euphemism for wlw

I’m high and I’m feeling anxious
 Inside of the CVS

In a tour diary shared by NPR, Bridgers wrote about how she loves to wander around drug stores while on tour:

When I was mixing my record in Nebraska, before I really knew anyone there, I drove myself to Target on Halloween and spent three hours walking around. I think I bought socks. In The White Album, Joan Didion writes about the role of malls in the ‘sedation of anxiety.’ At shows, there is always a weird amount of time between load-in and soundcheck. Not enough to do something, but too much to do nothing, so usually I go for a walk. Nine times out of ten, if I see a CVS, I will go in, and nine times out of ten I will buy nothing.

Similarly, in her song “Punisher,” on her sophomore album of the same name, Bridgers sings:

The drugstores are open all night
The only real reason I moved to the east side
I love a good place to hide in plain sight

description.plain:
“Anything But Me” is MUNA’s second single from their 2022 self-titled album, and their second release through Phoebe Bridgers‘ Saddest Factory record label. The song sees them hope their ex-lover gets everything, hope they do in fact change, but refuse to stick around just on that hope.

The song and music video was released on March 15, 2022, along with the album’s announcement and dates for the band’s fall 2022 tour. In the music video, the band is imprisoned in various positions, metaphorically by the ex-lover.

annotations: I want to dance in the middle of a gay bar

One of MUNA’s first big hits was “I Know A Place” which references a place to dance, be safe and be yourself.

Here, they place they know and want to be is a gay bar.
Put something on her tongue
MUNA is referencing acid tabs here which are placed on the tongue to dissolve.

I’ve spent way too-too-too many years not knowing what
 What I wanted, how to get it, how to live it and now
 I’m gonna make up for it all at once

This song—and these lines in particular—capture the idea of a queer “second adolescence.” Many queer people, for a variety of reasons, don’t get the chance to live out the classic coming of age, teenage experiences of their cishet peers—falling in love, being reckless and making mistakes, etc; so they end up living their “teenage years” later on in life, often in their twenties or thirties.

description.plain:
“I Know A Place” is the lead single from LA-based group MUNA’s debut album About U. It premiered on December 2, 2016.

The song was released a few months after the 2016 Orlando shooting at a gay club. “I Know A Place” celebrates peace, love, and equality. In an interview with iHeartRadio, the members of the all-female band said:

We wrote ‘I Know a Place’ to be like a contemporary anthem for the queer community. The LGBT community. We started writing it in 2015 after the Supreme Court decision to legalize gay marriage, and it was a really celebratory song, but we also knew that there were a lot of people in our community who still don’t feel safe. So we wrote it also as a message of safety and nonviolence. And then it took on a new meaning after the Orlando shooting.

The song instantly became an anthem for the safety of the LGBTQ community, as declared by TIME Magazine.

annotations:
’Cause maybe our purpose
 Is to never give up when we’re on the right track
The queer community is on a path to healing. Despite all the pain that still exists, queer people need to stick together and remember that they’re loved.

’Cause I can recall when I was the one in your seat
 I still got the scars and they occasionally bleed
 ’Cause somebody hurt me
 Somebody hurt me
 But I’m staying alive

It takes a while for the emotional wounds to heal from not being accepted by loved ones. The singer is farther on their healing journey than the one they’re singing to, but they understand how it feels just the same.
But you’re here by my side
Despite the obstacles that queer people face because of bigotry, the community finds comfort and empowerment by staying together and supporting each other.

I, I know a place where you don’t need protection
 Even if it’s only in my imagination
In a worst case scenario, where the world falls apart, and no where is safe, MUNA is providing a place where their friend needs no protection, which is her imagination; by MUNA’s side.

They will try to make you unhappy
 Don’t let them
 They will try to tell you you’re not free
 Don’t listen

There will always be people that will try to tear down the progress we’ve made and try to spread hate and fear just because they don’t understand someone. MUNA is trying to tell us to not let their words get to us and continue forward.
But if you want to go out dancing
MUNA is inviting their friend to a place of distraction and solace where they can be themselves and not fear others judging them for who they really are.

And it’s hard to love
 With a heart that’s hurting
‘With a heart that’s hurting’, it’s difficult to love because emotions like sadness and anger usually overpower love in most situations.

You think being yourself
 Means being unworthy

Often members of the LGBTQ community can develop self hatred and loathing due to common cases of bullying. This can lead to people thinking that when they are themselves, they will always be treated badly and they are unworthy of being themselves.

And I can tell
 When you get nervous

Often, LGBTQ people have to hide their true selves due to fear of experiencing homophobia in public. With that comes nervousness and fear, and MUNA is able to tell that when they’re friend becomes nervous.

Right now
 It’s like you’re carrying all the weight of your past
 I see all your bruises, yellow, dark blue, and black

Often people focus on the bad things that happened in the past and let that define them as that is the brain’s way of defending one against ‘danger’. However, when that danger is unrealistic, the mind and body can become overburdened with pressure and cause ‘bruises’.

description.plain:
Home By Now is the fourth song released from MUNA’s self-titled album. The track reminisces on a past relationship that didn’t work out. Even though they are the one who initiated the break up, they wonder if they gave up on things too soon and if they eventually would have worked out. In the track, MUNA connects the dream of love with this person to a dream of home.

Said Gavin of the song:

‘Home By Now’ is the song on the record that we feel might be closest to our first album in that it’s a dance song with brutal lyrics and an emo bridge,” Katie Gavin said in a statement. “It’s a breakup song that’s a bit more full of longing and doubt than ‘Anything But Me.’ While a lot of this album does seem to be about trusting my instincts, this song acknowledges the pain of not knowing if I left a relationship that I was meant to be in.

Home By Now is the fourth song released from MUNA’s self-titled album. The track reminisces on a past relationship that didn’t work out. Even though they are the one who initiated the break up, they wonder if they gave up on things too soon and if they eventually would have worked out. In the track, MUNA connects the dream of love with this person to a dream of home.

Said Gavin of the song:

‘Home By Now’ is the song on the record that we feel might be closest to our first album in that it’s a dance song with brutal lyrics and an emo bridge,” Katie Gavin said in a statement. “It’s a breakup song that’s a bit more full of longing and doubt than ‘Anything But Me.’ While a lot of this album does seem to be about trusting my instincts, this song acknowledges the pain of not knowing if I left a relationship that I was meant to be in.

annotations:
Would we have turned a corner if I had waited?
 Do I need to lower my expectations?
 If we’d kept heading the same direction
 Would we be home by

In the pre-chorus, the singer states that the reason why the relationship ended was because the other person could not meet the singer’s needs, but now the singer is wondering if they were asking for too much and if they should have just given the person a chance

Have you ever heard about how when a person’s in a maze
 They will tend to walk in circles thinking they are going straight
 They can’t see the bigger picture so they get stuck in a loop
 In the end I was afraid that that’s what you and I would do
She was afraid the relationship would never go anywhere and didn’t want to waste any more time

Now I don’t know if I’d been okay with
 Holding out hope for your stack of rainchecks
 If I had been able to grin and bear it
 Would we be home by now
If the singer had pushed through the phase of canceling plans and being flakey maybe they would be in a happy, committed relationship by now

description.plain:
“Number One Fan” is a song about recognizing the negative voices in your head and—as hard as it may be—learning to speak back to them.

Despite the success of their first album About U, MUNA told Billboard that they still deal with self doubt.

There were a lot of moments in the first album cycle where we were having success and other people around us were saying, ‘You’re doing so well, you must be so happy.‘ and I think it’s common to actually have this inner turmoil of, ‘I don’t deserve this.’

This track takes a stab back at that doubt, counteracting it with self love.

body.plain:
“Number One Fan” is a song about recognizing the negative voices in your head and—as hard as it may be—learning to speak back to them.

Despite the success of their first album About U, MUNA told Billboard that they still deal with self doubt.

There were a lot of moments in the first album cycle where we were having success and other people around us were saying, ‘You’re doing so well, you must be so happy.‘ and I think it’s common to actually have this inner turmoil of, ‘I don’t deserve this.’

This track takes a stab back at that doubt, counteracting it with self love.

annotations:
If I’m born to lose
 I’ll never try and I will never learn, but

Believing that you’re ‘born to lose’ means you’ll never attempt anything, because you’ll assume failure. But by having enough self-belief to try, you might just succeed or pick up new knowledge and skills.

Love me in the way that only you can
 Be my number one, number one
Nobody else’s affection or attention can replace self-love, and they recognize that they need that kind of love in their life.

I would give my life just to hold your hand
 I’m your number one fan
 I’m your number one, number one fan”

Not only is she out of the dark place she was in where she hated herself, but she has adopted a new mindset and learnt to love herself. She is telling herself that she is her number one fan because she realises how special and worth loving she is and how important it is to remind herself that.

I’ve been looking at myself in the mirror, saying
 “Don’t leave me now,”
The repetition of this line emphasises how much she wants to stay alive because she has realised that she has so much left to live for and she deserves to live. She now loves life and herself.

I’ve been looking at myself in the mirror, saying
 “Don’t leave me now, don’t leave me now”

“Don’t leave me now” may be a reference to suicidal thoughts and the possibility of her not being there anymore. She was in a dark place and full of self-hatred, but now she has learnt to look at herself differently and no longer wants to end her own life.

MUNA also addresses suicide on If U Leave Me Now from their 2017 debut album, About U.
New hair and new shoes
Now that she sees how beautiful she is, her confidence has translated into the way she presents herself through her choice of clothing and hairstyle.

So here’s the bad news
 I’m coming for everyone and I’m coming on strong

In the first verse, she was comparing herself to strangers on social media, but now that she has learned to love herself she has a new-found confidence and realises that she is just as or even more beautiful than the people she sees online and used to compare herself to.
Looking at strangers on my telephone
The speaker is making their shame spiral worse by scrolling through social media– where everyone is more beautiful, more successful, and more popular than they are in real life.
Stan

The term “Stan” refers to the Eminem song about an obsessed stalker. According to the Oxford dictionary, a Stan is an “overzealous or obsessive fan of a particular celebrity.”

In the music video for “Stan”, the stalker is shown looking into the mirror, admiring himself – the same happens in the lyrics of “Number one fan”.

In the thick of it
 Will you stick up for me?
 In the thick of it
 Are you gonna believe that I can do it?
She is contemplating if she can be still be her own biggest fan in hard times.
